he wide-ranging ‘migration’ of Homeric material through time and across place holds significant cultural power, being instrumental in the construction of new cultural identities. The volume is of particular interest to scholars in the fields of classics, reception and cultural studies and the performing arts, as well as to readers fascinated by ancient literature and its cultural transformations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aEpic poetry, GreekxHistory and criticismvCongresses. 0aReader-response criticismvCongresses. 4aAntike. 4aGriechische Literatur. 4aHomer. 4aPerformanz. 4aRezeptionswissenschaften. 4aancient Greek literature. 4aperforming arts. 4areception studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aEfstathiou, Athanasios, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKaramanou, Ioanna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070100508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2016z9783110485097oZDB-23-DGD0 cEPUBz97831104791880 cprintz978311047783240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311047979940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110479799423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110479799.jpg  a978-3-11-070100-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGDb2016  aZDB-23-DGGb2016